What I Genuinely Dislike (Updated)
The alert engine is a ticking bomb. SP_ALERT_SCAN is now a single monolithic procedure with 15+ rule CTEs. One broken CTE (bad data type, null division, missing table) silently kills ALL alerting — the INSERT fails atomically. This is the #1 thing I'd fix before calling it production. Decompose into per-rule isolated execution with error capture per rule.

Detection without notification is theater. You can detect contract breach, fingerprint drift, volume drops, credential expiry, governance drift — but the only delivery mechanism is "open the app and look." A DBA asleep at 2am when the volume-drop alert fires will never see it until morning. Without NOTIFICATION INTEGRATION → email/webhook, half these rules provide delayed value. The webhook_delivery.sql file exists but it's opt-in and apparently not wired to the scan proc.

The Brief page doesn't go far enough. It's a good start, but it's still a Streamlit page you have to open. The truly elite version is: the Brief auto-generates as a Slack message or email at 6am, delivered to the DBA channel and the exec's inbox. The in-app version is the fallback, not the primary surface.

Governance drift score has the same calibration problem the platform score used to have. You fixed platform score (configurable weights via SETTINGS). But governance drift weights are still hardcoded (mfa * 5, expired * 8, breakglass * 6). Apply the same pattern — make them SETTINGS-driven. Otherwise you'll get the same "why is an MFA gap worth 5 but an expired credential worth 8?" question with no good answer.

The app still doesn't know if it's working. The canary checks dependency views exist, but there's no SLA on the app's own render time. If Overview takes 15 seconds to load, nobody knows except the frustrated user. Add client-side performance tracking (the telemetry infra exists — use it to fire an alert when p95 page render exceeds 5s).

Net Assessment
This is a meaningful improvement. You addressed 8 of my top 12 criticisms from Round 1 in what appears to be a single iteration. The changes are architecturally sound — no shortcuts, no cosmetic fixes pretending to be structural ones. The ML forecast pattern is textbook correct. The DT pilot rationale is defensible. The RUNBOOK transforms this from "a dashboard someone built" to "an operational system someone owns."

The gap between this and an elite enterprise platform is no longer architectural — it's workflow (alert delivery, closed-loop remediation) and polish (design system, multi-account). That's a good place to be.
